You can declare the variable and then assign it a value using the following syntax:
variable = value;
For example, to set the color of an object, you would use this statement:
color = #ff0000;
The variable can be of any type, including simple values like integers or strings. You can also use variables as parameters in procedures and methods.

You can compare the values of two variables or literals using the equal to operator (==). This checks whether the objects represented by the variables have identical attributes, such as their names or values. If they do not match, then the expression evaluates to false. For example:
if (x == y) {
// Do something here...
} else {
// Do something else here...
}

You can create objects of any type in Actian 4GL, including complex data types like arrays and enumerations. To do this, simply declare a variable of the desired type and then assign it to whatever value you want. For example, if you want to create an array with five integers, you could use code similar to this:
int[] myArray = new int[5];
myArray[0] = 10;
myArray[1] = 20;
myArray[2] = 30;
myArray[3] = 40;
myArray[4] = 50;
Now, this array has five elements with integer values between 10 and 50. You can access these elements using their index numbers or by calling methods on the array object itself. For example, if you wanted to get the third element in your array, you could use code like this:
int thirdElement = myArray[2];
Console.WriteLine("Third element is {0}", thirdElement);

You can insert a new row into any table using the following syntax:
insert into <table name>; (fields) = values (field1, field2, ...);
Here, <table name> is replaced with the actual name of the table you want to work with. The fields clause lists all the columns in order they should appear in the new row. You specify their names and any desired initial values using a comma-separated list. After executing this statement, Actian 4GL inserts the data into the database and updates any related indices automatically for you.

To create your own menu item, follow these steps:
1. Define the label text for the menu item using a literal string or variable reference. For example:
```
let title = 'Destruction';
```
2. Set its action property to the desired function that you want to call when users select it from their menus. You can use any valid JavaScript function here, such as a built-in method or your custom code:
```
title.action = function() {
// Code for destroying objects here...
};
```
3. Add the menu item to some container, such as another menu or toolbar. You can use any valid XDK reference here, such as its ID or name:
```
menuItem.addTo(toolbar);
```
4. Save your changes and test them in the IDE. If everything works properly, then you should see your new menu item appear in the appropriate place!

